Updated: I didn&#39;t realize that you use typescript, please disregard the original answer.

With typescript the capitalized imports should work if you have installed [@types/express][1] - because this package exports capitalized types: https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/master/types/express/index.d.ts#L86

Probably before the restart the types package has not been indexed somehow. This is the only guess that I have taking into account that the issue has been resolved. 

=======================================

When a module is imported - the file listed as the [main][2] is the `package.json` is loaded. If there is no `main` file in the `package.json` then `index.js` from the module root directory is loaded. 

In case of express there is no `main` file and `index.js` loads `./lib/express`:
https://github.com/expressjs/express/blob/master/index.js

    module.exports = require(&#39;./lib/express&#39;);

By checking `./lib/express` we can see that it exports `request`, `response` and `application` in lowercase:
https://github.com/expressjs/express/blob/master/lib/express.js#L59:

    /**
     * Expose the prototypes.
     */
    
    exports.application = proto;
    exports.request = req;
    exports.response = res;




So in order to import them you should use lowercase:

    import { response, request, application } from &#39;express&#39;; 


  [1]: https://www.npmjs.com/package/@types/express
  [2]: https://docs.npmjs.com/files/package.json#main

You want to lower case &#39;Request&#39;, &#39;Response&#39;, and &#39;Application&#39;.

